{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478062"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:08:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:08:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15292"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15292"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.57,0.09,0.09,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7983"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46381"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1083"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5981"},{"type":"tags","id":"7886"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43575"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a five-week history of rash and intermittent fevers. Her parent reports a rash that appears when she is febrile and disappears when the fever settles. She had febrile seizures as a toddler but none since the age of 4, and takes no regular medications. Her parents are heavy smokers and her mother smoked whilst pregnant with her.  Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a temperature of 38.9\u00b0C. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. There is a non-pruiritic salmon-pink macular rash on her trunk and proximal limbs that blanches on pressure. It spares the face, soles and palms.  Her right knee and left ankle are swollen and tender. The rash fades when her temperature normalises two hours later, except for a few plaques that persist.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura","Systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis","Kawasaki disease","Acute rheumatic fever","Viral exanthem"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis (JIA): fever, arthritis, and an evanescent salmon-pink rash. The characteristic feature of \u003Cstrong\u003Esystemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is the appearance of the rash during fever spikes and its complete disappearance when the temperature normalises.  Sometimes plaques or periorbital oedema may persist even with a normal temperature.  Children may also present similarly to adults with rheumatoid nodules and guttate and plaque psoriasis.  Koebner phenomenon is often present as well.  It may be associated with maternal smoking and antibiotics, but the exact cause of condition is unclear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with palpable purpura on the lower extremities and buttocks, along with abdominal pain and arthritis. The rash is non-blanching and does not vary with temperature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute rheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever and migratory polyarthritis, but its characteristic rash (erythema marginatum) is ring-shaped with central clearing and is uncommon in modern practice. There is also usually a history of recent streptococcal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki disease\u003C/strong\u003E presents with persistent fever and a polymorphous rash, but also includes other diagnostic criteria such as conjunctival injection, changes in the lips and oral mucosa, cervical lymphadenopathy, and changes in the extremities. The rash does not typically come and go with fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral exanthem\u003C/strong\u003E may cause fever and rash but typically does not cause significant arthritis. The rash usually persists throughout the illness rather than appearing and disappearing with fever spikes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of systemic JIA is primarily clinical, based on the presence of arthritis, daily fever for at least two weeks, and at least one of: evanescent rash, generalised lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, or serositis. Laboratory findings may include elevated inflammatory markers, neutrophilia, and thrombocytosis, but these are not specific.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The salmon-pink rash of systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis typically appears during fever spikes and disappears when temperature normalises.","The presence of a characteristic rash with fever and arthritis supports the diagnosis of systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis."],"references":["Chua-Aguilera CJ, M\u00f6ller B, Yawalkar N. Skin Manifestations of Rheumatoid Arthritis, Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis, and Spondyloarthritides. Clin Rev Allergy Immunol. 2017.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28752373/","Kim N Velykoredko Y, Oakley A, Mitchel G, McGivern M. Juvenile idiopathic arthritis.  DermNet NZ.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/juvenile-idiopathic-arthritis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46381"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15292"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46381"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-14T16:28:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-14T16:31:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7983"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60936"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoj